\# M\&A Dealmaker — Task System Specification



\## Purpose



This document defines the \*\*Task System\*\*, one of the core components of the M\&A Dealmaker simulation engine.



Tasks represent \*\*concrete actions performed by the advisory firm\*\*.



They translate player intent into:



\- resource consumption

\- progress in deal workstreams

\- narrative consequences

\- probabilistic outcomes



The system is designed to be \*\*generic\*\*, allowing reuse in other simulation games.



---



\# Conceptual Model



The player does not directly progress deals.



Instead, the player:



1\. decides \*\*what work needs to be done\*\*

2\. allocates \*\*resources to execute that work\*\*



The simulation engine converts those decisions into:



\- workstream progress

\- state changes

\- events



---



\# Task Definition



A task represents a \*\*unit of work\*\*.



Examples in M\&A context:



Prepare Founder Meeting

Build Buyer Universe

Conflict Check

Valuation Analysis

Draft Pitch Deck

Sector Research

Financial Intelligence Gathering



---



\# Task Structure



Each task contains three components.



\## 1. Inputs



Resources required to perform the task.



\### Time



Human hours required by role.



Example:



Partner: 1h

Associate: 3h

Analyst: 2h



---



\### Money



Financial cost.



Examples:



\- research databases

\- industry reports

\- outsourcing

\- consultants

\- travel



Example:



Cost: €3,000



---



\### Skills



Certain tasks may require capabilities.



Examples:



Valuation expertise

Sector expertise

Legal knowledge

Relationship capital



Skills influence \*\*efficiency and quality\*\*.



---



\# 2. Outputs



Tasks generate effects.



\### Workstream Progress



Tasks increase progress in one or more workstreams.



Example:



Prepare Buyer Landscape



Target Intelligence +15

Pitch Readiness +10



---



\### Information Gain



Some tasks reveal hidden information.



Examples:



\- revenue breakdown

\- customer concentration

\- competitive landscape

\- founder motivations



Information improves decision quality.



---



\### Variable Changes



Tasks may modify deal variables.



Examples:



Relationship meeting



Access Level +12

Lead Heat +5



---



\# 3. Risk



Tasks may trigger probabilistic outcomes.



Examples:



Competitor appears

Information leak

Founder hesitation

Unexpected buyer interest



Risk probabilities depend on variables such as:



Confidentiality Risk

Competitive Pressure

Market Sentiment



---



\# Internal vs Outsourced Execution



Most tasks can be executed in two ways.



\## Internal Execution



Consumes staff capacity.



Advantages:



lower cost

higher control

better learning



Disadvantages:



team workload increases

slower execution if team small



---



\## Outsourced Execution



Consumes financial resources.



Advantages:



faster execution

less team workload



Disadvantages:



higher cost

lower internal learning

potential information leakage risk



---



\# Task Efficiency



Task output depends on execution efficiency.



Efficiency is influenced by:



team experience

sector expertise

team morale

team workload



---



\## Efficiency Formula (Conceptual)



Progress = Effort × Efficiency × Quality



Where:



Effort = hours allocated

Efficiency = skill modifier

Quality = execution quality



---



\# Task Duration



Tasks may be:



Immediate

Same-day completion.



Multi-day

Progress accumulated over several days.



Examples:



Pitch Deck Preparation

Financial Analysis

Due Diligence Preparation



---



\# Task Categories



Tasks can be grouped into categories.



\## Deal Tasks



Specific to an opportunity.



Examples:



Founder meeting preparation

Buyer mapping

Valuation work



---



\## Firm Tasks



Strategic work affecting the whole firm.



Examples:



Hiring staff

Training employees

Networking events

Sector research programs



---



\## Maintenance Tasks



Operational work.



Examples:



Team management

Internal reviews

Compliance checks



---



\# Task Queue



The player defines a \*\*task queue\*\*.



Tasks are then executed based on:



available capacity

priority

resource constraints



The simulation engine resolves execution each cycle.



---



\# Task Dependencies



Some tasks require previous tasks.



Examples:



Valuation Analysis requires Financial Intelligence.



Buyer Outreach requires Buyer Landscape mapping.



Pitch Deck requires Qualification progress.



Dependencies ensure logical sequencing.



---



\# Task Priority



Players can assign priority levels.



High priority tasks receive resources first.



Low priority tasks may be delayed.



This becomes important when multiple deals compete for resources.



---



\# Task Failure



Tasks may fail.



Examples:



Meeting cancelled

Data unavailable

Incorrect assumptions



Failure may result in:



no progress

reduced morale

increased uncertainty



---



\# Task Data Structure (Conceptual)



Example representation.

